    <discussion>The Florida populations have been called Acanthocereus floridanus but now appear to
        be the northernmost variants of the highly variable species A. tetragonus, which occurs
        throughout the Caribbean region (D. R. Hunt 1991).</discussion>
    <discussion>The common name “triangle cactus” refers to the mature stems in cross section; the
        epithet “tetragonus” alludes to the juvenile stems, which often have four
        angles.</discussion>
